t successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Hughes was born in 1391, in Sleaford, Lincolnshire, England, his father, Raynold Hughes, was 22 and his mother, Eleanor Aubeny, was 28. He married Katherine Lumley in 1409, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1451, in Somme, Picardie, France, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1391–1451":"1391–1451","1396–1461":"1396–1461","1410–1478":"1410–1478","1411–1450":"1411–1450","1414–1500":"1414–1500","1417–1450":"1417–1450","1370–1392":"1370–1392","1364–1420":"1364–1420","1451":"1451","1396":"1396","1450":"1450","1461":"1461","1392":"1392","1370":"1370","1391":"1391","1414":"1414","1500":"1500","1478":"1478","1411":"1411","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1364":"1364","1409":"1409","1417":"1417","Seaford Linconshire":"Seaford, Tasman, Uus-Meremaa","Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","sleaford Lincolnshire":"Sleaford, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sleaford, Lincolnshire, England":"Sleaford, Lincolnshire, England","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England"},"fi":{"1391–1451":"1391–1451","1396–1461":"1396–1461","1410–1478":"1410–1478","1411–1450":"1411–1450","1414–1500":"1414–1500","1417–1450":"1417–1450","1370–1392":"1370–1392","1364–1420":"136